# ==============================================================================
# ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES - EXAMPLE FILE
# ==============================================================================
#
# This is a template showing what environment variables this app needs.
# Environment variables are configuration values that:
#   1. Contain sensitive information (API keys, secrets)
#   2. Change between environments (development vs production)
#   3. Should NOT be committed to version control
#
# HOW TO USE THIS FILE:
#   1. Copy this file and rename it to ".env"
#   2. Replace the placeholder values with your real credentials
#   3. NEVER commit the .env file to Git (it's in .gitignore)
#
# Example:
#   cp .env.example .env
#   then edit .env with your real values
#
# ==============================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SUPABASE CONFIGURATION
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Get these values from your Supabase project:
#   1. Go to https://supabase.com
#   2. Sign in and select your project (or create a new one)
#   3. Go to Settings > API
#   4. Copy the values below
#

# Supabase Project URL
# Format: https://xxxxxxxxxxxxx.supabase.co
# Example: https://abcdefghijklmnop.supabase.co
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=your-project-url-here

# Supabase Anonymous (Public) Key
# This is safe to use in client-side code
# It respects Row Level Security (RLS) policies
# Format: A long JWT token starting with "eyJ..."
# Example: eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJpc3MiOiJzdXBhYmFzZSIsInJlZiI6...
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key-here

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPORTANT NOTES
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# 1. EXPO_PUBLIC_ PREFIX:
#    In Expo, environment variables MUST start with EXPO_PUBLIC_ to be
#    accessible in your app code. This is a security feature.
#
# 2. SECURITY:
#    - The .env file is in .gitignore (won't be committed to Git)
#    - Never share your .env file publicly
#    - Never hardcode these values in your source code
#    - The anon key is safe for client-side use (mobile apps)
#    - The service_role key (if you have one) should NEVER be in the app
#
# 3. DEVELOPMENT vs PRODUCTION:
#    You might have different values for different environments:
#    - .env.development (for local development)
#    - .env.production (for production builds)
#    For now, one .env file is fine for learning!
#
# 4. RESTARTING THE APP:
#    After creating/modifying .env, restart your Expo dev server:
#    - Stop the current server (Ctrl+C)
#    - Run "npm start" again
#    Environment variables are loaded when the dev server starts
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# WHERE TO FIND YOUR SUPABASE CREDENTIALS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Step-by-step guide:
#
# 1. Create a Supabase account (if you haven't):
#    - Go to https://supabase.com
#    - Click "Start your project"
#    - Sign up with GitHub/Google/Email
#
# 2. Create a new project:
#    - Click "New Project"
#    - Choose an organization
#    - Enter project name (e.g., "pochoclo-learning")
#    - Enter a database password (save it somewhere safe!)
#    - Choose a region (closest to your location)
#    - Click "Create new project"
#    - Wait for project to set up (~2 minutes)
#
# 3. Get your credentials:
#    - Once project is ready, click "Settings" (gear icon)
#    - Click "API" in the left sidebar
#    - Find "Project URL" - copy this to EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
#    - Find "Project API keys" section
#    - Copy "anon/public" key to EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY
#
# 4. Create your .env file:
#    - Copy this file: cp .env.example .env
#    - Open .env
#    - Replace the placeholder values with your real values
#    - Save the file
#
# 5. Restart your app:
#    - Stop Expo (Ctrl+C in terminal)
#    - Run: npm start
#    - Your app can now connect to Supabase!
#
